Only placed 17 pieces of gear on this one! Need to run it out more. Kiwi guy Duncan hauled up his amp to this crag - one of the longer walk ins in Indian Creek, and played the wall album which was a great touch. 'Comfortably Numb' came on as I was about two thirds the way up. Awesome!
One last route to round off the day, should have gone for the lead on this one earlier on. A crack that goes through all the sizes, from hands down to finger tips.
Really awkward off balance start. Got a bit 'bloom-bagged' with gear on this one, needed more reds an greens.
A valley 5.6, total walk, but pleasant.
Had a slip on the calcite shit at the start of this. Kinda pumpy with the thin hands towards the top. Nice to be in the shade for this one, its long.

A beautiful, short and technical climb. Right facing finger corner, roof, then left facing finger corner. Got told this was 11a before getting on it, and it may as well have been. Quite different to the standard finger crack with no feet.

Easy warm up. Madison, Duncan and Khash played 'trad golf' on this one

Just wide enough to get a little pumpy!
Not actually that generic, lots of pods and roundedness. First climb in the creek and a good one to start on.

David pussied out of the top 5.8 pitch and went directly up then left and slightly poor rock. About vs.
Cool route on very good rock. A walk until halfway up though. Doubled up on cams for the yank and placed about 1, with the rest of them getting snagged on the rock!
A cool route, micronuts were useful. Probably around hvs. David lead the two 5.6 pitches and I ran the two 5.8 pitches together on one 70m rope.
Awesome juggy climbing that I have only done on limestone until now, much like the previous climb. Looked more juggy from the ground than it turned out to be though!
I think this was listed as a 10a in the Falcon guide, and is the best line at the crag, following a right diagonal thin crack to two bolts. Easier than the 5.9.
I think this may have been the first tightly bolted line we did. Once you have done one here, you may as well have done them all (apart from Blonde Dwarf), very samey.
Messed up the approach, but got there in the end. Mediocre climbing but another Yosemite summit.
Lead did not start. Roberto made it look hard then told me later that he used to climb 8c when he was younger.
Too easy.
Fucking awesome, the sort of stuff you come to Yosemite for. Finally a climb that translates properly in grade comparison tables.
1st 5.8 pitch only
Absolutely brutal though the top bit was easier. Need to get better at this sort of thing. Not want, need.
Simul climbed in 2 hours 23 minutes, starting at 7.52am as a way of getting to Crest Jewell. One of the shittest classic routes I have done.

Runout and scary in places with holds that are very subtle and hard to find. Led and linked pitches 1 and 2, and let Sam take the drivers seat a bit higher up, where we finally began to get used to the style. Great climb, not done anything quite like it.

Climb name: Cathedral Peak Southeast Buttress A B and C
Notes: Simul climb whip up this - apart from an an to retrieve a nut Andrey couldn't get out. Everyone else pitching and taking forever.
Started up the steep south face crack but then thought better of it, so did a big spiral around the pinnacle. Porn in the summit box!
Quite a cruise until the last 8 or so metres of thin hands. Led p 2, 4 and 5.
Led pin scar p1

Some of the quickest 13 pitches I've ever climbed. Not sure where the scrambling ended and climbing started. Simul all apart from the last 2 and led the alternative 5.8 finish which felt like a valley 5.6. Dip in the lake at the end of the day which was surprisingly warm. Great day out.
Fun upside down hand and foot jamming until halfway along where they thin out. One that I definitely have to get clean at some point in the future.
To retrieve gear. Aid practice.

In 11 pitches and approx 8 hours. Went wrong way on the last 5.9 pitch but it turned out to be a happy accident as we cut a corner off. Quite polished with a fair bit of loose and not that classic. Michael a bit put off by Felix memorial on 1st pitch.
Led p 2, 3 and 5. It snowed on the top 2 pitches. Great Alpine feeling route that I have been telling everyone I meet to do since.
Top two pitches of this one were sublime.
Michael's lead. Couldn't do the first bit and even found it hard to aid.
Strained stomach muscles in this, got the crux first move on second round of goes. Insecure, directional and balance classic Yosemite sandbag.
Getting Compo's cam out of this without falling off was a complete fucker.

Got up and down this quicker than before, and led the pitches I didn't lead last time. Matt found a way of doing the top pitch with gear, unlike me last time. Was amusing watching tourists on the way down crapping their pants due to the exposure and calling us crazy for walking on the outside of the cables. A lot less snow and glaciers visible in the high country compared to 4 years ago which was sad. All the hiking destroyed us for 2 days afterwards.

Led most of this, did the bolt ladder variation (and not 50 crowded) this time which was more like 11c, got about 3 clips up before the bolts got too far to the left, even Michael frigged this one! Probably more out of wanting to get up it asap though. More sustained climbing than I remember.
Stiff for 5.7
Same link cam that was stuck there 4 years ago is still there!

Was all going fine until I reached the 5.9 off width at the top. Schoolboy error wearing shorts with no socks and not bringing the number 6 cam. Slid up and down it a couple times getting within a couple foot of the finishing jugs, then got to the chains via the 5.7 chimney. So hot that day, more puffed out and dehydrated than I have ever been on one single pitch route, and got quite badly grazed up legs, should have paid more attention to beta in the book. Top end E2.
In four big / moving together pitches, in 2 hours. A well named climb, random slippery bits keep coming up!
One movey together pitch. Walked the flake part.
Lead crux pitch one. Topped out at 12.47am after starting from the bottom of the Apron at about 7.45am.
Just to get to Butt Light, so not really. Must come back and do it properly. 10c pitch looks cool!

Absolutely gutted to bail from this great looking climb. Did the alternative left traversing start, then right blocky corner, which was sandbagged at 5.8, then got stuck around 3 parties who were moving painfully slow at about 3.30pm. Should have got there earlier than 12.30am. David made the call to rap down, which is fair enough as we wouldn't have finished in the light, and we wouldn't have been able to pass the cunts. Dammit!
The most interesting route on Concord by far. Lead p1 + 3.
David ran p1 + 2 together and I lead the easy stegosaur pitch. Left rope in place for him to prussik up and down, then down climbed the pitch. Cool summit.

Fun climb, with crack climbing that isn't too sustained, lots of options for holds outside of the crack, and crack ranged from hands to chimney. Slight runout easy face climbing around a mid way bulge.

5.9+ in the guidebook, described by Alex as 5.9++. Solid UK E2, probably 5b. Lead the insecure flakes pitch with some blind gear placements (mental crux), and secure, burly offwidth corner pitch (physical crux). Topped out as the sun was going down, a great time be up there, but then again not! Back to the car around 10.30, a full day and great route!
Bit too high to want to make a lunge to an unknown hold on the crux, so I backed off.

Lead pitches 1, 3, and 5. The last pitch was great, but some douche had tick marked it, and its only a french 5! Great route and easy to find unlike the other routes on Goat Wall, which require a metal detector to locate!
Make it to the 3rd clip. Could not make the lunge to the sloper, just got worse after more attempts. Fun climb though.

Not sure if I did the correct start, but it seemed to fit the guidebook description. Approached via two fixed ropes, then dropped down to a 60 metre or so face. Did a 5.8 or so pitch higher up that I thought was the hand crack, then walked / scrambled a bit further to find the actual hand crack with was easy but a joy to climb.
Got snowed on on the 2nd belay!
Lead p1 and 3. Bit of  a crap climb, p2 was a walk, but made up for by the final alpine style arête thing.
Sweet route.

Good varied climbing. Really enjoyed the flared chimney offwidth thing. Total sandbag, but I'm learning the yosemite decimal system merely describes the width of the crack. Led P1 and P2 after Austin backed off of it.
As onsight as it could be after mistaking the direct start for the 10a.
Awkward climbing.
Much easier than people were making it look, probably HVS. Not much harder than The File.
First 5.12a! Brilliant pumpy climbing through the overhanging section without any really hard moves, and a bit goey again at the top. I would guess E5 6a.
tr'd in one big pitch. Fire in the disco.
One reachy move for the crux, first half was cruisy. Probably E2.
One of the most sustained hand cracks I have done to date, brilliant. Would want about 10 yellow cams for the lead!

Pleased to finish the day by cleaning something up.
So this is what top end e3 feels like! Made it to the final crux, but missed the crucial crimp first time round.

Brilliant climb, classic bold E2 5b. Marked as six pitches in the select guide, I ran 1 and 2 together, than Tom ran 3 and 4 together. Tom took a worried looking selfie with me and a number 1 nut in in the background on pitch 5, which was class. Hell of a walk in for one route, but at least it was a good one.
Tom's lead
Nice to do something a bit longer. Seems the most worthwhile of the lines here.

Bailed off the lead as I was getting a bit pumped and didn't want to blow the move onto the slab and risk a groundfall. Absolutely breezed it on top rope. Mad how much difference fiddly gear can make.
Not too nice with sweaty feet in the heat, but kept it together.

Really damn good. Tom's favourite line at the Head. I led pitch 1 and 3, he led the steep pitch 2, which suits him perfectly. Had the priviledge of meeting Calvin and Clare afterwards, who Tom thanked for such an awesome route. Calvin said the first pitch originally had chockstones, which fell out, making it harder. Had abbed down to do Blockbuster, but glad to get on this instead. An eye opener and confidence booster for Tom indeed.

A brilliant route and totally worth the effort (if someone abseiled down and spent a day or two cleaning it)! Still, the route chose me and Martin - not the other way around - so we HAD to do it.

I was the only fucker who decided to ab in with a climbing rope, so we probably didn't get started til late afternoon after someone else brought a rope down for us. Martin backed off the first pitch due to loose rock, so Kat led it. I led p2, which had a lot of onion skinning rock in the crack to look out for, and a lovely, steep solid hand crack followed by a couple face moves to finish on. Catherine thought she liked chimneys, but it turns out she doesn't, so I had to take the lead on p3. Not as bad as the top pitch of Raglan Road, at all. And solid rock there. Topped out around 11pm, missed the Honnold lecture, but I'd rather see him climb gnarly shit than hear him talk anyway. Kat got the hump with me for a couple days, Martin took it on the chin as a learning experience. Great line, the middle pitch just needs a clean.
E2 with 2 metres of harder climbing. Bit of an ego massage.
Hard E1. It's no Cenotaph Corner people, come on. Tom lead the first pitch, I the second. Nice climb.
Led pitch 2. Agree with Dan. Awesome crux bit that's a little bit out there!
Quick romp at the end of the day. The day that Mr. Honnold used my ab rope!
Led the second pitch. Very nice sustained jamming. No way this is E1, just HVS. Awesome line and awesome belay position at the top.

First E3 of the year. Guidebook says it's low in the grade, but definitely found it harder than GBH and Marconi. Very sustained. Somehow managed to use up nearly all my draws by the time I reached the flake- ledge, so Catherine kindly lowered some to me. Interesting moves up the final corner.
Bit of a nasty first half, with bad, hollow sounding rock. Tested a peg I clipped out left before the traverse and pulled it out. Tom then made it into a necklace for me.

Proper adventure! Led the middle pitch. Care with route finding required at the top of p2 for those of us who prefer to climb things that aren't green and unprotectable. Somehow managed to top out at 7pm.
Tom's first route at Fair Head
Bit bold in the central section, but fine.
A pleasant warm up

I made this far harder than 5a, hard to see how it would go at that grade. However Tom used the holds I used for my hands on the traverse for feet, and made far easier work of it, the bastard! A good exercise in slabby traversy balancing for me, I guess. Bold at the top.

Absolutely awesome route, and good send off to the Mournes. Didn't find it that hard for the grade, there are plenty of good rests to be found and the final pull through the overhang is short lived and so fun!
A nice route, good jamming practice if you can handle rough granite.

You would have to be on crack to give this route any stars at all, let alone 3. Too much broken ground, ledges and crap to give you bad rope drag by the time you finally get to the meat of the route, which would feel like 5a if you weren't pulling undergrowth up with you.
Very hard for the grade, had to resort to some sport climber moves to recover at the top of the first pitch! Agree with the other guy; GBH on the prow is easier than this!

Lovely bridging and stuff with the flutings.
